The code of conduct establishes the presence of an Italian police officer on board ships such as Iuventa to monitor activities.
Only three of the nine non-profit organisations involved in rescue operations have so far agreed to comply with the code: Save The Children, Maltese MOAS and the Spanish Pro-Activa Open Arms.
The latter organisation said on Thursday that the new rules were not necessary but acceptable as they did not represent any "substantial change or obstacle" to the rescue operations.
The adoption of the new code of conduct was rejected, for example, by the organisation Doctors Without Borders (MSF), which holds the Nobel Prize.
Meanwhile, MINNITI let it be heard that the sharp decline in immigrants in recent weeks disembarking in Italy as part of rescue operations suggests that efforts to boost patrols off the coast of Libya and cooperation with local mayors bear fruit.
