Lavender from Provence threatens climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the southeastern France region, but they are now threatened by climate change.
Lavender is dwindling due to dry climate and harmful insects, causing consternation on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence, said: "Growing lavender in Provence is at risk because over the past few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, bringing with it less rainfall in the spring and autumn.
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
The cicadas and grasshoppers carrying the micro-bacteria that thrive in the dry climate are also to blame. "
There is much at stake.
Lavender attracts tourists, and the oil produced from them is an important component of perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: 'Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, undeveloped and often weak plants grow.
The amount of oil obtained from this lavender is understandably smaller. "
A possible solution may be more efficient water distribution and slowing the evaporation of water from the soil, but also spraying the lavender protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more species resistant to dry weather.
