An article in the journal Current Biology said it was' the most preserved yet-to-be-found armoured dinosaur and one of the best dinosaur species in the world '.
The fossil is a new species of the Nodosauridae family.
His perfectly preserved condition literally shocked the researchers, who described it with the words' truly remarkable '.
According to National Geographic, it is the best preserved fossil of its kind.
Behind the find is Shawn Funk, who uncovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Canadian Alberta.
He came across what appeared to be a foreign object and decided to examine it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover the animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1100 kg.
After completing the works, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
"All you have to do is squint your eyes a little and believe they're asleep," said labor leader Caleb Brown and the naturalist of the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is exposed.
"It will certainly go down in the history of history as one of the most beautiful and preserved species of dinosaur - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
By studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank - was very likely to face a serious threat from the flesh-eating dinosaurs.
The heavily armoured dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators, using a camouflage system used by many of today's animals.
Experts say this allowed him to better blend in with his surroundings and avoid enemies.... The camouflage system suggests he was the favourite food of the larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110 million-year-old dinosaur of the Nodosauridae family first appeared in a newspaper in May.
The researchers gave him the name Borealopelta maroscilchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who along with the team spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the wonderfully preserved state of the fossil, Dr Mitchell and an international team of scientists could document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They revealed the method of camouflage commonly used by today's animals in defence - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers' findings are surprising because Borealopeltam's size far exceeds today's animals using the same technique.
It is possible, then, that the dinosaur was such a multitude of predators that evolution gave survival priority to camouflage before confrontation.
Many contemporary animals with camouflage - such as deer, zebra, or armadillo - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the carrier had to literally fight for its survival.
"The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur illustrates the dangers posed by predators in the chalk period," Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic ingredients contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin probably had a reddish-brown colour.
Researchers are continuing to study the animal and are searching for more knowledge about his life, including preserved stomach contents to track down his last meal.
It is believed the dinosaur after death fell into the river and was taken to the sea where it sank to the bottom.
In the Alberta area at the time, there was the same climate as in today's Florida, and rivers and oceans stretched much farther inland than is the case today.
"It is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin and is preserved in three dimensions and so you can see its original size," Brown said.
"For these reasons, the animal looks virtually the same as it did at the time of the chalk.
