A Becoming Resemblance: Artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of New York's Fridman Gallery, there are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and dark - hanging from the ceiling on the wire.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg of swabs from the oral cavity and hair sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cables to WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which launched on August 2, bears the title A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines his experiences with technology, informatics and art, and Manning - a transgender and pioneering dissident whose punishment was reduced by Obama three days before his departure from the post of US president.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and by using 30 portraits to depict what a person would look like with this genotype, Dewey-Hagborg created a razor-thin, if not intellectual, comment about DNA yielding - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identities.
Manning, who was born as Bradley Edward Manning, has spoken since her youth about being considered a woman.... She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of 20 indictments, including violating six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All her photographs were held by prison staff; only one black-and-white photograph in lower quality escaped to the public, to which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in the platinum blonde wig with which she is now associated.
In 2015, there were still positive responses to Dewey-Hagborg's 2012 Stranger Visions project.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and they wanted to supplement the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained on the occasion of the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visits or photography were not allowed, so they turned to Chelsea asking if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse made friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, who presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibition in person.
Indeed, a few days after the comic's release, President Obama asked for Manning's release, which was a welcome change after several excruciating years in a military prison in Kansas.
Indeed, it is interesting that the exhibition takes place just as Donald Trump is waging a war of words with people seeking to publish government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways for his tweets to incite resentment in areas he should support.
In response to a query about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything happens for a reason."
Under a statement from an artist on one of the gallery's walls, Manning calls her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is dotted with the heart) after the end of "self-inflicted fractionation based on gender, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite side are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By listing 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist's sophisticated scientific vocabulary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least on the biological side, we all are.
"I hope people take away from it that our genome doesn't matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret them in their own way," Dewey-Hagborg said.
'DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them.'
The last copy of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging in the manner of King Kong from the United States Disiplinary Barracks with a megaphone in his hand.
"Once they prevent you from making a speech, they win," she writes.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia-based artist stated.
"When I think about it, it gives me the creeps."
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition in person - which was predicted in the comic book - but when she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room by her masks, her own genome effigies, lined up like a crowd of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including a nearly 160-inch-tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
"They've been placed on the walls in the past, but this time I wanted them to suck the feeling of the crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates it."
