"We will complete the WADA plan in the near future" - Vice-President of the Russian government Mutko
Vice President of the Russian government Vitaly Mutko said it would not take long to implement the remaining criteria of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) and the re-provision of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
'at present, part of the criteria of the new plan has already been completed and RUSADA has already acquired the right to planning and testing in partnership with the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
In light of this, the WADA plan has been updated, "Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice President commented on the second part of WADA's plan to comply with the Code - which describes the criteria for the renewal of RUSADA - which was recently published on the organisation's website.
According to Mutko, the code contains nothing to worry Russia.
"Everything has been announced and everything will be implemented as well.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near term, "he added.
One of those criteria, however, calls for a public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation, investigated by Richard McLaren, about the alleged sponsorship of doping by Russian athletes by the government.
On the subject, Mutko said: "We are conducting an investigation as our anti-doping system has clearly failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs in our country, and we cannot confess to something that never existed. "
Mutko's words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview for Russia's RSport, Smirnov admitted the problems of Russian anti-doping officials, but added: "On many occasions we have stated that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report entirely without reservation, "Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSADA of handing out doping controls within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organisation has authorised planning and unification testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) this June.
After visiting the Moscow headquarters of the organization in July, WADA chief executive Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was "on the right track" to resume.
