Making a graphic novel: The Story of A Castle in England
The small castle of Scotney Castle recently played a leading role in the Squeeze group's music video, and its refuge in it was also found by Margaret Thatcher during the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cosy spot at the River Bewl in British Kent, which inspired the curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of Yorkshire County - a known fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
"Looking at the writing of a person who is 300 years after death fascinates me," Rhodes says with a straight face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the life of the families who survived at Castle Scotney from the Middle Ages to the Eduardo period.
However, it is not the first Rhodes book inspired by the archives: He is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by documents from the British Library - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by a thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jakobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those times you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
How I love the archives! "
For someone who is so fascinated by the old papers, the support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and the chance to dwell on almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream. ("To tell you the truth, I have extended my stay a little longer.")
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, passing through archives and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of hyenas on the wall and bottles that had been dumped for centuries in a ditch.
Walking around the property and exploring the ruins of the old castle, he spoke to gamekeepers, gardeners and occasionally also with artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
At night, he "drank whiskey and wrote."
The confidential history of Scotney is a relatively large unknown as the National Trust organisation gained access to the documents only in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site a decade later, staff were only beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described in words as when "the aristocrats of many centuries spread their hands with the words:" Leave it in the attic. ""
Diaries, letters from the days of the British Empire, maps depicting the majesty: "You might think the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were dragging on a birch.
Stop it, people! "
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a stepping stone and delve deeper into English history, including a story titled The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
"I found a record of a riot at the castle from 1380, which in the book was dubbed the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex," Rhodes said.
'the English uprising actually started in this area and I thought rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they're connected in the end. "
Other stories are firmly linked to the castle's history - such as The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest sheltered by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the coffin was uncovered).
Rhodes' favourite family are Darrell's: "I was intrigued by the male generation - the then-men were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family dealt with it by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to hang their heads with heiresses. "
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes is searching for more adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week gig in the Finnish wilderness, where he was soaking up the inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former nursing home from the early 20th century that was engulfed by nature.
For Scotney, however, it is a special place.
"I was sad when I left," he stated.
"I was like," Now to get the hell back in real life. ""
