But a new study suggests the opposite: A diet rich in animal protein and dairy could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The untreatable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million US residents and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to use meat and dairy products to alleviate symptoms. Washington University researchers found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that support bowel resistance.
Study leader Dr Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the gut and ensure the degradation of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the bowls of the scales tilt to the side of inflammation, an inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, researchers found the presence of immune cells promoting body tolerance in the stomach of mice with specific bacteria.
This bacteria requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to create cells.
Professor Colonna said: 'We found a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that promote body tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells. "
At the same time, he suggested that if it turns out the same applies to humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
Graduate researcher Dr Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwasa, as part of studying a certain type of immune cells supporting body tolerance, discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while a second group of the same mice kept separate cells missing.
She deduced that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and moulds that routinely dwell in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mouse's gut was tested by the DNA-sorting method, and researchers found six species of bacteria in mice with immune cells missed by a second group of mice.
The mice, which were bred in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome - thus did not develop this kind of immune cells - were given the bacterium L. reuteri - and formed immune cells.
To understand how the bacteria affects the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without the bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mouse diet, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in their gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known if the byproducts of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes were found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan added: 'Each of us should probably aim to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the bowel.
A potentially high level of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri may increase the cell population. "
