British inventor uses microchip in his hand to unlock car and house by wave
A British inventor has become the first person in the country with a microchip injected into his body - with a simple wave of his hand he can unlock the door from the house and office and even start the car.
Thirty-three-year-old Steven Northam has kept the tiny chip implanted between his thumb and index finger and is currently offering the same service through his company BioTeq to firms and individuals who want to make life easier through technology.
Dr Geoff Watson, an anesthesiologist at the Royal Hampshire County Hospital in Winchester, is supervising the procedure for implantation and compliance with treatment procedures.
The technology works on the same principle as microchips implanted in dogs and cats, and the whole procedure takes 30 seconds.
Northam's company also offers a service to exchange door locks and cars compatible with a microchip. The price of one lock is £300.
