White House prop cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter on the South Lawn to the occasion of a celebration of the U.S. manufacturing industry that took place last month came, according to Navy records released by the weekly TIME, at $24,000.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a parade of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials have touted a parade of products from all 50 states.
A Connecticut helicopter was exposed next to a yacht from Maine, a Wisconsin fire truck and a forked lift cart from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentation order, or Frago, and applied for a helicopter presence less than 36 hours before landing a helicopter on the South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, said Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - the units responsible for helicopter management.
"I wanted to make sure you had awareness of such a momentous event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his supervisor, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation the day before the event began.
The report suggested the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn on July 17 at about 7pm on the occasion of the parade, the start of which is scheduled for 15: 00 and will remain in place until the entire site is fully cleared, which was planned between 18: 00 and 21: 00.
In an email, it further said that if there was a delay in taking off from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight because of working-time regulations.
The original crew remained at the scene that evening along with the helicopter and, along with them, a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by the weekly TIME - it was not apparent if a second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prevents state officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records suggest HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this regulation.
"We wondered if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that all was well," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy leader wrote.
This "Made in America" parade was designated by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act would therefore not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his attendance at the event, the president championed health reform going through the Senate and talked about trying to keep government regulations in check.
The use of aerial vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered scrutiny in February after a presidential plane taxied in the background at his first-ever rally during a campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida.... His Twitter account is overwhelmed with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
"The White House is pleased with the parade of" Made in America, "which introduced products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials," said deputy press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and the South Lawn, and rehearse possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the current crew training, a state official said.
The helicopter unit on the same day urged an additional eleven hours under "non-presidential support missions."
The White House said no other props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
A spokesperson for Sikorsky said the company was not in any way involved in negotiations over the exposure of the helicopter to the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost in connection with the parade is difficult to determine, according to the Navy's statement.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal 2017, reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24380 per flight hour.
The unit's records list a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter move well below that amount.
"Putting the cost to taxpayers based on estimates for reimbursement of expenses is very misleading," Walters said of the whole thing.
"These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual cost."
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD spending refunds do not include the cost of personnel, but include the price of fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
Then-White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for parade purposes.
"The idea of the parade taking place this week is to introduce products manufactured in the U.S.," Spicer said.
'I'm aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state, and that they provide work to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and the other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact must be remembered. "
It is not clear if Trump, during his rounds on the South Lawn, was also to look at the helicopter.... It is certain to say only that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
